<subSubSection id="C9C6F1F7FF5BCE8BFCD5F9A4DE183B5F" pageId="214" pageNumber="215" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8163A27CFF5BCE8BFCD5F9A4DE183B5F" blockId="214.[810,1452,1653,1980]" pageId="214" pageNumber="215">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF5BCE8BFCD5F9A4D8F73AA1" bold="true" box="[810,932,1653,1679]" pageId="214" pageNumber="215">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
According to 
<bibRefCitation id="E54DDF8DFF5BCE8BFB90F9A4D8243A9B" author="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A." pageId="214" pageNumber="215" pagination="1 - 83" refId="ref140496" refString="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A. (2018) Taxonomic revision and morphology of the trapdoor spider genus Actinopus (Mygalomorphae: Actinopodidae) in Argentina. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 419, 1 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 - 419.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff (2018)</bibRefCitation>
, males of 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF5BCE8BFC18F94ADF913A9A" authorityName="Rios" authorityYear="2014" box="[999,1218,1690,1717]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="214" pageNumber="215" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="goloboffi">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF5BCE8BFC18F94ADF913A9A" box="[999,1218,1690,1717]" italics="true" pageId="214" pageNumber="215">Actinopus goloboffi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from those of 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF5BCE8BFC1CF911DF3E3AF4" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff" authorityYear="2018" box="[995,1133,1728,1754]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="214" pageNumber="215" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="balcarce">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF5BCE8BFC1CF911DF3E3AF4" box="[995,1133,1728,1754]" italics="true" pageId="214" pageNumber="215">A. balcarce</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="46DCD9FFFF5BCE8BFB49F911DE1F3AF4" authorityName="Rios-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff" authorityYear="2018" box="[1206,1356,1728,1754]" class="Arachnida" family="Actinopodidae" genus="Actinopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="214" pageNumber="215" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="excavatus">
<emphasis id="B3A87E6EFF5BCE8BFB49F911DE1F3AF4" box="[1206,1356,1728,1754]" italics="true" pageId="214" pageNumber="215">A. excavatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of a projection in the anterior angle of coxae I–II (
<bibRefCitation id="E54DDF8DFF5BCE8BFCCEF8DADFC13B0B" author="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A." box="[817,1170,1803,1829]" pageId="214" pageNumber="215" pagination="1 - 83" refId="ref140496" refString="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A. (2018) Taxonomic revision and morphology of the trapdoor spider genus Actinopus (Mygalomorphae: Actinopodidae) in Argentina. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 419, 1 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 - 419.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff 2018</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 41 B). Females have subquadrate spermathecae, with a protruding external lobe (
<bibRefCitation id="E54DDF8DFF5BCE8BFC97F887DF9E3B5F" author="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A." box="[872,1229,1878,1905]" pageId="214" pageNumber="215" pagination="1 - 83" refId="ref140496" refString="Rios-Tamayo, D. &amp; Goloboff, P. A. (2018) Taxonomic revision and morphology of the trapdoor spider genus Actinopus (Mygalomorphae: Actinopodidae) in Argentina. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 419, 1 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 - 419.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Ríos-Tamayo &amp; Goloboff 2018</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 42 C).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
